        "difficulty": "Hard",
        "question": "Let $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ be the roots of $x^2+\\sqrt{3} x-16=0$, and $\\gamma$ and $\\delta$ be the roots of $x^2+3 x-1=0$. If $P_n=$ $\\alpha^n+\\beta^n$ and $Q_n=\\gamma^n+\\hat{o}^n$, then $\\frac{P_{25}+\\sqrt{3} P_{24}}{2 P_{23}}+\\frac{Q_{25}-Q_{23}}{Q_{24}}$ is equal to",
        "options": [
          "4",
          "3",
          "5",
          "7"
        ],
        "correctOptionIndex": 2,
        "solution": "$$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Rightarrow \\quad P^n=\\gamma^n+\\delta^n \\\\\n& P_{25}-P_{23}=\\left(\\gamma^{25}-\\gamma^{23}\\right)+\\left(\\delta^{25}-\\delta^{23}\\right) \\\\\n& =\\gamma^{23}\\left(\\gamma^2-1\\right)+\\delta^{23}\\left(\\delta^2-1\\right) \\\\\n& =\\gamma^{23}(-3 \\gamma)+\\delta^{23}(-3 \\delta)=-3\\left[\\gamma^{24}+\\delta^{24}\\right]\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n&\\Rightarrow \\frac{P_{25}-P_{23}}{P_{24}}=(-3)\\\\\n&\\text { Similarly, }\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Rightarrow Q_{25}+\\sqrt{3} Q_{24}=\\left(\\alpha^{25}+\\sqrt{3} \\alpha^{24}\\right)+\\left(\\beta^{25}+\\sqrt{3} \\beta^{24}\\right) \\\\\n& =\\alpha^{23}\\left(\\alpha^2+\\sqrt{3} \\alpha\\right)+\\beta^{23}\\left(\\beta^2+\\sqrt{3} \\beta\\right) \\\\\n& =\\alpha^{23}(16)+16 \\beta^{23} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\frac{Q_{25}+\\sqrt{3} Q_{24}}{2 \\cdot Q_{23}}=\\frac{16\\left(\\alpha^{23}+\\beta^{23}\\right)}{2\\left(\\alpha^{23}+\\beta^{23}\\right)}=8 \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\frac{Q_{25}+\\sqrt{3} Q_{24}}{2 Q_{23}}+\\frac{\\left(P_{25}-P_{23}\\right)}{P_{24}}=8+(-3)=5\n\\end{aligned}$$",
