        "correctOptionIndex": 0,
        "solution": "Given\n\n$$P_n=\\alpha^n+\\beta^n$$\n\nand\n\n$$P_{10}=123,\\quad P_9=76,\\quad P_8=47,\\quad P_1=1.$$\n\nWe want the quadratic equation whose roots are $\\dfrac{1}{\\alpha}$ and $\\dfrac{1}{\\beta}$.\n\nFor numbers $\\alpha,\\beta$, the sequence $P_n=\\alpha^n+\\beta^n$ satisfies\n\n$$P_n=(\\alpha+\\beta)P_{n-1}-(\\alpha\\beta)P_{n-2}.$$\n\nNow use the given values:\n\n$$P_{10}=(\\alpha+\\beta)P_9-(\\alpha\\beta)P_8.$$\n\nSo,\n\n$$123=(\\alpha+\\beta)\\cdot 76-(\\alpha\\beta)\\cdot 47.$$\n\nAlso, since $P_1=\\alpha+\\beta=1$, we get\n\n$$123=76-47\\alpha\\beta.$$\n\nThus,\n\n$$47=-47\\alpha\\beta,$$\n\nso\n\n$$\\alpha\\beta=-1.$$\n\nNow the roots needed are $\\dfrac{1}{\\alpha}$ and $\\dfrac{1}{\\beta}$.\n\nTheir sum is\n\n$$\\frac{1}{\\alpha}+\\frac{1}{\\beta} =\\frac{\\alpha+\\beta}{\\alpha\\beta} =\\frac{1}{-1}=-1.$$\n\nTheir product is\n\n$$\\frac{1}{\\alpha\\beta}=\\frac{1}{-1}=-1.$$\n\nA quadratic equation with roots $r_1,r_2$ is\n\n$$x^2-(r_1+r_2)x+r_1r_2=0.$$\n\nHere,\n\n$$x^2-(-1)x+(-1)=0,$$\n\nwhich gives\n\n$$x^2+x-1=0.$$\n\nSo the correct option is:\n\n$$\\boxed{x^2+x-1=0}$$\n\nOption A.",
