        "solution": "We are given\n\n$$ \\lim_{x \\to 2} \\frac{\\tan(x-2)\\left(rx^2+(p-2)x-2p\\right)}{(x-2)^2}=5. $$\n\nWe have to first find the relation between $r$ and $p$, and then determine all values of $q$ for which the roots of\n\n$$ rx^2-px+q=0 $$\n\nlie in $(0,2)$.\n\nStep 1: Simplify the limit\nLet\n\n$$ f(x)=rx^2+(p-2)x-2p. $$\n\nThen the given limit becomes\n\n$$ \\lim_{x\\to 2}\\frac{\\tan(x-2)\\,f(x)}{(x-2)^2}=5. $$\n\nNow, as $x\\to 2$,\n\n$$ \\tan(x-2)\\sim x-2. $$\n\nSo the limit becomes\n\n$$ \\lim_{x\\to 2}\\frac{(x-2)f(x)}{(x-2)^2} = \\lim_{x\\to 2}\\frac{f(x)}{x-2}. $$\n\nFor this limit to be finite, we must have\n\n$$ f(2)=0. $$\n\nNow,\n\n$$ f(2)=r(2)^2+(p-2)(2)-2p=4r+2p-4-2p=4r-4. $$\n\nSo,\n\n$$ 4r-4=0 \\implies r=1. $$\n\nThen\n\n$$ f(x)=x^2+(p-2)x-2p. $$\n\nSince $f(2)=0$, factor $(x-2)$:\n\n$$ x^2+(p-2)x-2p=(x-2)(x+p). $$\n\nHence the limit becomes\n\n$$ \\lim_{x\\to 2}\\frac{\\tan(x-2)(x-2)(x+p)}{(x-2)^2} = \\lim_{x\\to 2}\\frac{\\tan(x-2)}{x-2}(x+p). $$\n\nUsing\n\n$$ \\lim_{t\\to 0}\\frac{\\tan t}{t}=1, $$\n\nwe get\n\n$$ 1\\cdot (2+p)=5. $$\n\nSo,\n\n$$ p+2=5 \\implies p=3. $$\n\nThus,\n\n$$ r=1,\\qquad p=3. $$\n\nStep 2: Form the quadratic equation\nNow the equation becomes\n\n$$ x^2-3x+q=0. $$\n\nWe want both roots to lie in $(0,2)$.\n\nLet the roots be $\\alpha_1,\\alpha_2$. Then\n\n$$ \\alpha_1+\\alpha_2=3,\\qquad \\alpha_1\\alpha_2=q. $$\n\nSince both roots lie in $(0,2)$, let us find the condition on $q$.\n\nStep 3: Use condition for both roots in $(0,2)$\nLet\n\n$$ f(x)=x^2-3x+q. $$\n\nSince coefficient of $x^2$ is positive, parabola opens upward.\n\nFor both roots to lie in $(0,2)$, we need:\n\n1. Real roots\nSo discriminant must be non-negative:\n\n$$ \\Delta=9-4q\\ge 0 \\implies q\\le \\frac94. $$\n\n2. Both roots positive\nSince product of roots is $q$,\n\n$$ q>0. $$\n\n3. Both roots less than $2$\nNow check value at $x=2$:\n\n$$ f(2)=4-6+q=q-2. $$\n\nIf both roots are less than $2$, then for an upward parabola, point $x=2$ lies to the right of both roots, so we need\n\n$$ f(2)>0. $$\n\nThus,\n\n$$ q-2>0 \\implies q>2. $$\n\nNow combine:\n\n$$ 2So the set of all possible values of $q$ is\n\n$$ (\\alpha,\\beta]=(2,\\tfrac94]. $$\n\nHence,\n\n$$ \\alpha=2,\\qquad \\beta=\\frac94. $$\n\nTherefore,\n\n$$ 4(\\alpha+\\beta)=4\\left(2+\\frac94\\right) =4\\left(\\frac{17}{4}\\right)=17. $$\n\nFinal Answer\n$$ \\boxed{17} $$\n\nSo, the correct option is Option C.",
