        "questionId": "pyq_mnswhxz2",
        "year": "JEE Main 2026 (online 4th april evening shift)",
        "difficulty": "Medium",
        "question": "If the quadratic equation $(\\lambda+2) x^2-3 \\lambda x+4 \\lambda=0, \\lambda \\neq-2$, has two positive roots, then the number of possible integral values of $\\lambda$ is :",
        "options": [
          "1",
          "2",
          "3",
          "4"
        ],
        "correctOptionIndex": 1,
        "solution": "For the quadratic equation  \n\n$$ (\\lambda+2)x^2-3\\lambda x+4\\lambda=0,\\qquad \\lambda\\neq -2 $$\n\nto have two positive roots, let us use the NCERT conditions for a quadratic equation.\n\nIf the roots are $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$, then for both roots to be positive, we need:\n\nDiscriminant $\\ge 0$ so that roots are real,\n\nSum of roots $>0$,\n\nProduct of roots $>0$.\n\n1. Identify coefficients\nComparing with $ax^2+bx+c=0$, we get\n\n$$ a=\\lambda+2,\\qquad b=-3\\lambda,\\qquad c=4\\lambda $$\n\n2. Condition for real roots\nDiscriminant:\n\n$$ D=b^2-4ac $$\n\nSo,\n\n$$ D=(-3\\lambda)^2-4(\\lambda+2)(4\\lambda) $$\n\n$$ D=9\\lambda^2-16\\lambda(\\lambda+2) $$\n\n$$ D=9\\lambda^2-16\\lambda^2-32\\lambda $$\n\n$$ D=-7\\lambda^2-32\\lambda $$\n\nFor real roots,\n\n$$ -7\\lambda^2-32\\lambda \\ge 0 $$\n\n$$ -\\lambda(7\\lambda+32)\\ge 0 $$\n\nMultiplying by $-1$ reverses the inequality:\n\n$$ \\lambda(7\\lambda+32)\\le 0 $$\n\nThis gives\n\n$$ -\\frac{32}{7}\\le \\lambda \\le 0 $$\n\nSo possible integral values from this condition are\n\n$$ \\lambda=-4,-3,-2,-1,0 $$\n\nBut given $\\lambda\\ne -2$, so remaining are\n\n$$ \\lambda=-4,-3,-1,0 $$\n\n3. Condition for sum of roots positive\nSum of roots is\n\n$$ \\alpha+\\beta = -\\frac{b}{a}=\\frac{3\\lambda}{\\lambda+2} $$\n\nFor two positive roots,\n\n$$ \\frac{3\\lambda}{\\lambda+2}>0 $$\n\nSince $3>0$, this means\n\n$$ \\frac{\\lambda}{\\lambda+2}>0 $$\n\nThis is positive when numerator and denominator have same sign:\n\n$\\lambda>0$ and $\\lambda+2>0$, or\n\n$\\lambda\n\nSo,\n\n$$ \\lambda>0 \\quad \\text{or} \\quad \\lambdaFrom our shortlisted values $-4,-3,-1,0$, this keeps only\n\n$$ \\lambda=-4,-3 $$\n\n4. Condition for product of roots positive\nProduct of roots is\n\n$$ \\alpha\\beta=\\frac{c}{a}=\\frac{4\\lambda}{\\lambda+2} $$\n\nFor positive roots,\n\n$$ \\frac{4\\lambda}{\\lambda+2}>0 $$\n\nAgain,\n\n$$ \\frac{\\lambda}{\\lambda+2}>0 $$\n\nThis gives the same condition:\n\n$$ \\lambda>0 \\quad \\text{or} \\quad \\lambdaAmong the shortlisted values, again we get\n\n$$ \\lambda=-4,-3 $$\n\n5. Check both values\n\nFor $\\lambda=-4$:\n\n$$   D=-7(16)-32(-4)=-112+128=16>0   $$\n\nSo roots are real and distinct.\n\nFor $\\lambda=-3$:\n\n$$   D=-7(9)-32(-3)=-63+96=33>0   $$\n\nSo roots are real and distinct.\n\nHence both values give two positive roots.\n\nTherefore, the number of possible integral values of $\\lambda$ is\n\n$$ \\boxed{2} $$\n\nSo, the correct option is B.",
