        "questionId": "pyq_mnricktg",
        "year": "JEE Main 2026 (online 2nd april morning shift)",
        "difficulty": "Medium",
        "question": "Let $\\alpha, \\alpha+2, \\alpha \\in \\mathbf{Z}$, be the roots of the quadratic equation $x(x+2)+(x+1)(x+3)+(x+2)(x+4)+\\ldots .+(x+\\mathrm{n}-1)(x+\\mathrm{n}+1)=4 \\mathrm{n}$ for some $\\mathrm{n} \\in \\mathbf{N}$. Then $\\mathrm{n}+\\alpha$ is equal to :",
        "options": [
          "0",
          "1",
          "2",
          "3"
        ],
        "correctOptionIndex": 2,
        "solution": "We are given that  \n\nthe quadratic equation is  \n\n$ (x)(x+2) + (x+1)(x+3) + (x+2)(x+4) + \\ldots + (x + n - 1)(x + n + 1) = 4n $\n\nand the roots are $ \\alpha, \\alpha + 2 $ (both integers).  \n\nWe need to find the value of $ n + \\alpha $.\n\nStep 1: Expand the general term\nThe $k^{th}$ term of the left-hand side is:\n\n$ (x + k)(x + k + 2) $\n\nExpanding this:\n\n$ (x + k)(x + k + 2) = x^2 + 2(k+1)x + k(k+2) $\n\nStep 2: Sum over all $k$ from $0$ to $n-1$\n$ \\text{LHS} = \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} [x^2 + 2(k+1)x + k(k+2)] $\n\nLet's compute each part separately.\n\nFor $x^2$:\n\n$    \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} x^2 = n x^2    $\n\nFor $2(k+1)x$:\n\n$    \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} 2(k+1)x = 2x \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (k+1) = 2x \\cdot \\frac{n(n+1)}{2} = n(n+1)x    $\n\nFor $k(k+2)$:\n\n$    \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} k(k+2) = \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (k^2 + 2k) = \\sum k^2 + 2\\sum k    $\n\nNow,\n\n$ \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} k = \\frac{n(n-1)}{2}, \\quad \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} k^2 = \\frac{(n-1)n(2n-1)}{6} $\n\nTherefore,\n\n$ \\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} k(k+2) = \\frac{(n-1)n(2n-1)}{6} + n(n-1) $\n\nSimplify:\n\n$ = n(n-1)\\left( \\frac{2n-1}{6} + 1 \\right) = n(n-1)\\left( \\frac{2n-1+6}{6} \\right) = \\frac{n(n-1)(2n+5)}{6} $\n\nStep 3: Combine all terms\n$ \\text{LHS} = n x^2 + n(n+1)x + \\frac{n(n-1)(2n+5)}{6} $\n\nThe equation is\n\n$ n x^2 + n(n+1)x + \\frac{n(n-1)(2n+5)}{6} = 4n $\n\nStep 4: Simplify by dividing both sides by $n$ (since $n > 0$)\n$ x^2 + (n+1)x + \\frac{(n-1)(2n+5)}{6} = 4 $\n\n$ x^2 + (n+1)x + \\left[\\frac{(n-1)(2n+5)}{6} - 4\\right] = 0 $\n\nSimplify the constant term:\n\n$ \\frac{(n-1)(2n+5)}{6} - 4 = \\frac{(n-1)(2n+5) - 24}{6} = \\frac{2n^2 + 3n -29}{6} $\n\nThus, the equation is\n\n$ x^2 + (n+1)x + \\frac{2n^2 + 3n - 29}{6} = 0 $\n\nStep 5: Use relation between roots and coefficients\nLet roots be $ \\alpha $ and $ \\alpha + 2 $.\n\nThen,  \n\nSum of roots:\n\n$ \\alpha + (\\alpha + 2) = 2\\alpha + 2 = - (n+1) $\n\nso,\n\n$ \\alpha = \\frac{ - (n+1) - 2}{2} = -\\frac{n+3}{2} $\n\nProduct of roots:\n\n$ \\alpha(\\alpha + 2) = \\frac{2n^2 + 3n - 29}{6} $\n\nSubstitute $ \\alpha = -\\frac{n+3}{2} $:\n\n$ \\alpha(\\alpha + 2) = \\left(-\\frac{n+3}{2}\\right)\\left(-\\frac{n-1}{2}\\right) = \\frac{(n+3)(n-1)}{4} $\n\nStep 6: Equate the two expressions for product\n$ \\frac{(n+3)(n-1)}{4} = \\frac{2n^2 + 3n - 29}{6} $\n\nSimplify:\n\n$ 3(n+3)(n-1) = 2(2n^2 + 3n - 29) $\n\nExpand:\n\n$ 3(n^2 + 2n - 3) = 4n^2 + 6n - 58 $\n\n$ 3n^2 + 6n - 9 = 4n^2 + 6n - 58 $\n\nSimplify:\n\n$ 3n^2 + 6n - 9 - 4n^2 - 6n + 58 = 0 $\n\n$  -n^2 + 49 = 0 \\implies n^2 = 49 $\n\n$ n = 7 \\text{ (since } n \\in \\mathbf{N}) $\n\nStep 7: Find $ \\alpha $ and hence $ n + \\alpha $\n$ \\alpha = -\\frac{n+3}{2} = -\\frac{7+3}{2} = -5 $\n\n$ n + \\alpha = 7 + (-5) = 2 $\n\n$ \\boxed{n + \\alpha = 2} $\n\nCorrect Option: C (2)",
        "topic": "relation-between-roots-and-coefficients",
        "type": "mcq",
        "marks": 4,
        "negativeMarks": 1,
        "chapter_name": "Quadratic Equations",
        "chapterId": "quadratic_equation_and_inequalities"
